        {
            "title": "Adaptive Path Integral Smoother",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": null,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2016
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": null,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2018
                }
            },
            "description": "I implemented a parallel version of the Adaptive Path-Integral Smoother (APIS) using mpi4py. APIS is an adaptive importance sampler targeting the joint smoothing distribution, or posterior over hidden processes, in a state-space model. Using APIS improves the efficiency of the posterior sampling several orders of magnitude and the estimations obtained are more accurate than the standard backward particle methods. \nThese results, obtained with a simpler non-parallel implementation, were published in IEEE TSP (https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/7885094).",
            "contributors": [
                {
                    "type": "standardizedContributor",
                    "first_name": "Hans-Christian",
                    "last_name": "Ruiz Euler",
                    "name": null,
                    "headline": "Machine Learning Expert | Team Player | Diligent"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "title": "Network Estimation from Time Series Data",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": null,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2017
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": null,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2018
                }
            },
            "description": "I applied the Expectation-Maximization algorithm with APIS for fMRI time series. With this algorithm, I estimated the causal connectivity from fMRI toy data and analyzed the impact of different assumptions in the model on connectivity estimates.\nThe results are summarized in a paper \"Effective Connectivity from Single Trial fMRI Data by Sampling Biologically Plausible Models\" (https://arxiv.org/abs/1803.05840).",
